{"version":"0.3.1","atoms":[],"cards":[["markdown",{"markdown":"The core of any good Star Trek series is its crew. The crew is the heart of the ship and drives the story. In *Librarium Stellaris*, the focus is on the five main crewmembers who keep the ship running.

* **Captain Nyxian Vel** is the point of view character and technical head of the ship. It's her responsibility to maintain the collection and seek out new aquisitions for the archive. She is part of a species of goo-like shapeshifters called the *Odonians*, who are able to take a variety of forms depending on the situation. Odonians cannot take a single form for an extended period of time, so they use robotic suits to maintain a humanoid shape for longer periods. Captain Vel had hers modeled after a domestic feline from Earth because she thought they were cute.
* **First Officer Emi** "}]],"markups":[["em"]],"sections":[[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"I've talked a bit on the blog about my science fiction podcast, but I haven't gone into detail about the premise or anything. I've been more verbose over on Mastodon, but I thought I'd go into more detail on here and basically give a summary on what the project is all about."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[0],1,"Librarium Stellaris"],[0,[],0," is an audio-drama consisting of the mission logs of Captain Nyxian Vel of the Galactic Archive Ship the Alexandria. The Alexandria's mission is to travel the galaxy, collecting new information and literature while also distributing literature to the various cultures of the Milky Way. Its heavily inspired by classic "],[0,[0],1,"Star Trek"],[0,[],0," and "],[0,[0],1,"Star Trek: The Next Generation"],[0,[],0,", and my hope is that it will come across as more hopeful and utopian in tone. That being said, it won't be all sun and roses, and the Alexandria will face both internal and external challenges as it jounreys across the galaxy."]]],[10,0],[1,"p",[]]]}
